    <section class="content-section">
      <div class="container content-grid">
        <div class="main-content">

          <div class="definition-box">
            <p>Thornhill sits between Markham and Richmond Hill — a mature, well-established community with a significant Chinese-Canadian population alongside Russian and Israeli communities. Family law cases in Thornhill often involve <strong>uncontested divorces where one spouse is uncooperative, RRSP and investment account division, marriage contracts, and cross-border asset questions</strong> for families with ties to China. Miao He (何淼) provides full Mandarin family law services to Thornhill clients from her Markham office, minutes away. LSO #83315K · China Bar Association Licensed.</p>
          </div>

          <h2>Family Law Issues Common in Thornhill's Chinese-Canadian Community</h2>
          <p>Thornhill's Chinese-Canadian community spans multiple generations — from established families who have been in Canada for decades to more recent arrivals still navigating two legal systems simultaneously. The family law needs here reflect that range.</p>

          <h3>Uncontested Divorce: When Both Sides Agree</h3>
          <p>If both spouses agree on all terms — property division, support, and parenting arrangements — an uncontested divorce in Ontario can be completed without appearing in court. This is faster, less expensive, and far less stressful than contested litigation. Miao He drafts Separation Agreements that cover all required terms in legally enforceable language, and guides clients through the desk order process fully in Mandarin. Many Thornhill clients who initially think they need court ultimately proceed by agreement.</p>

          <h3>When a Spouse Won't Cooperate: Contested Divorce</h3>
          <p>If your spouse refuses to participate in the divorce process — ignoring communications, refusing to disclose assets, or simply delaying — Ontario law does not require their cooperation after one year of separation. Miao He can proceed on a unilateral basis, serving the respondent through appropriate channels and obtaining court orders for financial disclosure where needed.</p>

          <h3>RRSP, TFSA, and Investment Account Division</h3>
          <p>Thornhill families often have significant retirement savings — RRSPs, TFSAs, defined contribution plans, and non-registered investment portfolios. All of these must be valued at the correct date of separation and included in the Net Family Property calculation. Division of RRSPs can be accomplished through a direct transfer between plans without immediate tax consequences — Miao He advises clients on how to structure this efficiently.</p>

          <h3>Marriage Contracts: Protecting Pre-Marital and Family Assets</h3>
          <p>Thornhill Chinese-Canadian families frequently hold assets that existed before the marriage — property in China, funds from parents, or pre-marital savings — that they want protected from Equalization. A properly drafted Marriage Contract can exclude these assets. For the contract to be enforceable, both parties must have received independent legal advice. Miao He drafts contracts in Mandarin and English and provides independent legal advice to clients reviewing existing agreements.</p>

          <h3>Cross-Border Asset Division: China and Canada</h3>
          <p>Many Thornhill Chinese-Canadian families hold property, bank accounts, or business interests in China. A Canadian divorce covers global assets — property in China is not exempt from the Equalization calculation. Miao He's dual licences in Ontario and China allow her to address these assets directly, advising on disclosure obligations, valuation approaches, and enforcement mechanisms across both jurisdictions.</p>

          <div class="qa-block">
            <h3>Q: Can I get divorced in Ontario without going to court?</h3>
            <p>A: Yes — if both spouses agree on all issues, an uncontested divorce can be completed through a desk order process without a court appearance. Miao He can prepare the Separation Agreement and guide the full process in Mandarin. Call 647-930-6688.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-block">
            <h3>Q: If I divorce in Canada, does my marriage automatically end in China too?</h3>
            <p>A: No. A Canadian divorce order does not automatically dissolve the marriage under Chinese law. If you need to remarry in China or resolve property held there, additional steps are required. Miao He holds both Ontario and China bar licences and can advise on cross-border marital status. Call 647-930-6688.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="qa-block">
            <h3>Q: Which court handles Thornhill family law cases?</h3>
            <p>A: Thornhill is in York Region. Cases are heard at the Superior Court of Justice — Newmarket Courthouse, 50 Eagle Street West, Newmarket. Miao He is familiar with this court and can represent you fully in Mandarin. Call 647-930-6688.</p>
          </div>

